WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.110 --> 00:00:01.747
PRESENTER: Please
welcome Allie Brosh.

00:00:01.747 --> 00:00:04.299
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:04.299 --> 00:00:05.840
ALLIE BROSH: OK, so
I'm going to read

00:00:05.840 --> 00:00:08.550
you the first story in the book.

00:00:08.550 --> 00:00:10.700
So if you haven't
read the book yet,

00:00:10.700 --> 00:00:13.787
you're getting a head start.

00:00:13.787 --> 00:00:15.370
Let me make sure my
clicker's working.

00:00:18.990 --> 00:00:22.480
When I was 10 years old, I
wrote a letter to my future self

00:00:22.480 --> 00:00:24.600
and buried it in my backyard.

00:00:24.600 --> 00:00:26.370
17 years later, I
remembered that I

00:00:26.370 --> 00:00:29.922
was supposed to remember to
dig it up two years earlier.

00:00:29.922 --> 00:00:31.880
I looked forward to
getting a nostalgic glimpse

00:00:31.880 --> 00:00:32.989
into my childhood.

00:00:32.989 --> 00:00:34.780
Perhaps I would marvel
at my own innocence,

00:00:34.780 --> 00:00:37.840
or see the first glimmer
of my current aspirations.

00:00:37.840 --> 00:00:40.500
As it turns out, it just made
me feel real weird about myself.

00:00:45.130 --> 00:00:46.980
The letter was scrawled
in green crayon

00:00:46.980 --> 00:00:48.739
on the back of the utility bill.

00:00:48.739 --> 00:00:50.280
My 10-year-old self
had obviously not

00:00:50.280 --> 00:00:53.092
spent much time planning
out the presentation of it.

00:00:53.092 --> 00:00:55.550
Most likely, I had simply been
walking through the kitchen,

00:00:55.550 --> 00:00:57.140
and suddenly realized
it was entirely

00:00:57.140 --> 00:00:59.170
possible to write a
letter to my future self.

00:01:06.810 --> 00:01:08.980
The overwhelming excitement
of this realization

00:01:08.980 --> 00:01:11.180
probably cause me to
panic and short circuit,

00:01:11.180 --> 00:01:13.822
making me unable to locate
proper writing elements.

00:01:13.822 --> 00:01:15.530
There was no time for
that kind of thing.

00:01:19.336 --> 00:01:21.710
I did, however, manage to
fight through the haze of chaos

00:01:21.710 --> 00:01:24.240
and impulse long enough to
find a crayon stub and a paper

00:01:24.240 --> 00:01:25.430
surface to match it against.

00:01:29.010 --> 00:01:31.030
The letter begins thusly.

00:01:31.030 --> 00:01:32.620
"Dear 25-year-old."

00:01:32.620 --> 00:01:36.330
Note, not dear 25-year-old
me, or dear 25-year-old self.

00:01:36.330 --> 00:01:37.355
Just dear 25-year-old.

00:01:40.060 --> 00:01:41.310
Do you still like dogs?

00:01:47.600 --> 00:01:48.950
What is your favorite dog?

00:01:51.638 --> 00:01:53.300
Do you have a job training dogs?

00:01:56.050 --> 00:01:57.055
Is Murphy still alive?

00:02:02.227 --> 00:02:02.810
Foreshadowing.

00:02:06.320 --> 00:02:08.229
What is your favorite food?

00:02:08.229 --> 00:02:09.479
Are mom and dad still alive?

00:02:13.397 --> 00:02:15.855
I feel it's important to note
the order of those questions.

00:02:20.370 --> 00:02:23.360
Obviously, dog-related
subjects were my chief concern.

00:02:23.360 --> 00:02:25.820
Murphy was my family's
dog, followed closely

00:02:25.820 --> 00:02:27.719
by the need to know my
future favorite food.

00:02:27.719 --> 00:02:29.260
I feel that the
double question marks

00:02:29.260 --> 00:02:30.640
speak to how important
that question was.

00:02:30.640 --> 00:02:32.223
And you guys can't
see that, but there

00:02:32.223 --> 00:02:34.330
were double question
marks in there.

00:02:34.330 --> 00:02:36.580
Only then did I pause to
wonder whether my parents had

00:02:36.580 --> 00:02:38.624
survived.

00:02:38.624 --> 00:02:48.880
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:48.880 --> 00:02:52.020
The letter continues with a
section titled, "About Me."

00:02:52.020 --> 00:02:54.490
My name is Allie, and
I am 10 years old.

00:02:54.490 --> 00:02:56.039
I have blonde hair
and blue eyes.

00:02:56.039 --> 00:02:57.580
My favorite dog is
a German Shepherd.

00:02:57.580 --> 00:02:59.310
My second favorite
dog is a husky.

00:02:59.310 --> 00:03:01.190
My third favorite dog
is a Doberman Pinscher.

00:03:04.120 --> 00:03:07.304
This is troubling for a number
of reasons, the first of which

00:03:07.304 --> 00:03:09.470
is that I apparently thought
my future self wouldn't

00:03:09.470 --> 00:03:11.518
be aware of my
name or eye color.

00:03:11.518 --> 00:03:23.064
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:23.064 --> 00:03:24.730
The second thing is
the fact that I just

00:03:24.730 --> 00:03:26.360
tacked on my favorite
dog breeds at the end

00:03:26.360 --> 00:03:28.810
there, like it was every bit
as important to my identity

00:03:28.810 --> 00:03:31.580
as the other things, as if
my past self had imagined

00:03:31.580 --> 00:03:34.304
my future self standing in the
yard, above the upturned earth,

00:03:34.304 --> 00:03:35.720
clutching my letter
and screaming,

00:03:35.720 --> 00:03:37.510
but what dogs did I like?

00:03:40.310 --> 00:03:43.160
How am I supposed to understand
my identity without knowing

00:03:43.160 --> 00:03:44.525
what dogs I liked when I was 10?

00:03:48.182 --> 00:03:49.890
I take a break from
writing at that point

00:03:49.890 --> 00:03:52.514
to draw several pictures of what
appear to be German shepherds.

00:04:01.149 --> 00:04:03.690
Below the German shepherds, I
wrote the three most disturbing

00:04:03.690 --> 00:04:06.920
words in the entire letter,
three words that revealed more

00:04:06.920 --> 00:04:08.710
about my tenuous
grasp on reality

00:04:08.710 --> 00:04:11.590
than anything else I have
uncovered about my childhood.

00:04:11.590 --> 00:04:13.370
There at the bottom
of the letter,

00:04:13.370 --> 00:04:15.050
I had taken my
crayon stub and used

00:04:15.050 --> 00:04:17.130
it to craft the
following sentence.

00:04:17.130 --> 00:04:18.513
"Please write back."

00:04:18.513 --> 00:04:27.910
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:27.910 --> 00:04:30.620
Judging by the thick,
purposeful lines in each letter,

00:04:30.620 --> 00:04:33.340
I was applying a truly
impressive amount of pressure

00:04:33.340 --> 00:04:34.760
to the crayon.

00:04:34.760 --> 00:04:37.204
The sincerity of the
request is unmistakable.

00:04:37.204 --> 00:04:39.370
When I asked my future self
what my favorite dog is,

00:04:39.370 --> 00:04:41.370
or whether my mom and
dad were still alive,

00:04:41.370 --> 00:04:44.000
I actually expected
to get answers.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:46.220
And apparently, I still
expected to be 10 years old

00:04:46.220 --> 00:04:47.967
when I got those answers.

00:04:47.967 --> 00:04:48.800
"Please write back."

00:04:48.800 --> 00:04:50.980
I imagine myself patiently
standing in the yard,

00:04:50.980 --> 00:04:52.897
day after day,
thinking, any time now.

00:04:52.897 --> 00:04:53.980
It's going to happen soon.

00:04:53.980 --> 00:04:54.840
I just know it.

00:04:59.600 --> 00:05:01.250
Time travel is a
complex subject that I

00:05:01.250 --> 00:05:03.900
don't expect a 10-year-old
to fully understand.

00:05:03.900 --> 00:05:06.385
But this is more than just
a basic misunderstanding

00:05:06.385 --> 00:05:07.010
of time travel.

00:05:10.468 --> 00:05:29.760
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:31.700
I'm almost definitely
not a time traveler.

00:05:31.700 --> 00:05:34.330
But in case I am, I
decided to write back.

00:05:34.330 --> 00:05:36.160
In fact, I decided
to write letters

00:05:36.160 --> 00:05:37.970
to several iterations
of my past self,

00:05:37.970 --> 00:05:40.053
because I felt there were
important things I could

00:05:40.053 --> 00:05:42.470
explain to myself or things
I could warn myself about.

00:05:42.470 --> 00:05:45.400
Allow me to begin with a
letter to my two-year-old self.

00:05:45.400 --> 00:05:55.211
Dear two-year-old, face
cream is not edible.

00:05:55.211 --> 00:05:56.960
No matter how much it
looks like frosting,

00:05:56.960 --> 00:05:58.381
no matter how many
times you try,

00:05:58.381 --> 00:06:00.630
it's always going to be face
cream and never frosting.

00:06:04.289 --> 00:06:06.080
I promise I wouldn't
lie to you about this.

00:06:06.080 --> 00:06:07.788
It's honestly never
going to be frosting.

00:06:12.660 --> 00:06:14.565
For the love of
fuck, please stop.

00:06:17.582 --> 00:06:19.610
I need those organs
you're ruining.

00:06:25.729 --> 00:06:26.520
Dear four-year-old.

00:06:30.450 --> 00:06:32.380
Allow me preface this
by saying that I don't

00:06:32.380 --> 00:06:36.380
know why you started eating
salt in the first place.

00:06:36.380 --> 00:06:38.690
But regardless of the
precipitating circumstances,

00:06:38.690 --> 00:06:40.220
there you are.

00:06:40.220 --> 00:06:43.000
As soon as you became aware
that eating huge amounts of salt

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:46.945
is really, really
uncomfortably salty,

00:06:46.945 --> 00:06:50.790
you should have
stopped eating salt.

00:06:50.790 --> 00:06:52.560
That's the solution.

00:06:52.560 --> 00:06:54.580
The solution is not
to begin eating pepper

00:06:54.580 --> 00:06:55.680
to cancel out the salt.

00:07:01.410 --> 00:07:04.000
You've found yourself in this
predicament several times now.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.458
And every time, you get trapped
in this totally preventable

00:07:06.458 --> 00:07:07.080
cycle.

00:07:07.080 --> 00:07:08.570
You've done more than
enough experimenting

00:07:08.570 --> 00:07:10.403
to come to the conclusion
that pepper is not

00:07:10.403 --> 00:07:12.837
the opposite of salt
all by yourself.

00:07:12.837 --> 00:07:14.920
But somehow, you seem to
remain stubbornly unaware

00:07:14.920 --> 00:07:15.550
of this fact.

00:07:18.448 --> 00:07:26.190
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:26.190 --> 00:07:28.630
To reiterate, no matter
how much pepper you eat,

00:07:28.630 --> 00:07:30.520
it won't undo the
ludicrous amount of salt

00:07:30.520 --> 00:07:31.834
you ate before it.

00:07:31.834 --> 00:07:34.000
The only thing you're
accomplishing by eating pepper

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.000
is making your mouth taste
like pepper and salt.

00:07:39.270 --> 00:07:41.064
Similarly, switching
back to salt

00:07:41.064 --> 00:07:42.480
again won't cancel
out the burning

00:07:42.480 --> 00:07:46.100
from the pepper you ate to
cancel out the original salt.

00:07:46.100 --> 00:07:48.460
How is this so
difficult to understand?

00:07:48.460 --> 00:07:50.210
You can stop whenever
you want to do.

00:07:53.050 --> 00:07:55.014
As a side note, you
really need to start

00:07:55.014 --> 00:07:56.180
learning from your mistakes.

00:07:56.180 --> 00:07:57.680
Believe me, I know
what happens when

00:07:57.680 --> 00:07:59.640
you discover electric
fences next year.

00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:02.056
And you could do without that
seventh jolt of electricity.

00:08:04.874 --> 00:08:05.665
Dear five-year-old.

00:08:12.410 --> 00:08:13.850
What the fuck is wrong with you?

00:08:17.310 --> 00:08:19.850
Normal children don't have
dead imaginary friends.

00:08:22.860 --> 00:08:24.982
Normal children don't
pick open every single one

00:08:24.982 --> 00:08:26.440
of their chicken
pox scabs and then

00:08:26.440 --> 00:08:28.580
stand naked and bleeding
in the darkened doorway

00:08:28.580 --> 00:08:31.570
to their bedroom until
someone walks past and asks

00:08:31.570 --> 00:08:34.370
what they are doing.

00:08:34.370 --> 00:08:37.005
Furthermore, normal children
don't respond by saying,

00:08:37.005 --> 00:08:39.130
I wanted to know what all
my blood would look like.

00:08:43.774 --> 00:08:45.940
Normal children also don't
watch their parents sleep

00:08:45.940 --> 00:08:48.650
from the corner of their room.

00:08:48.650 --> 00:08:51.259
Mom was really scarred by "The
Exorcist" when she was younger,

00:08:51.259 --> 00:08:53.550
and she doesn't know how to
cope with your increasingly

00:08:53.550 --> 00:08:54.950
creepy behavior.

00:08:54.950 --> 00:08:55.930
Please stop.

00:08:55.930 --> 00:08:58.730
Please, please stop.

00:08:58.730 --> 00:09:00.969
Dear six-year-old.

00:09:00.969 --> 00:09:03.010
You're having an absurdly
difficult time learning

00:09:03.010 --> 00:09:14.815
the letter R. You
practice all the time,

00:09:14.815 --> 00:09:17.190
and you have mastered every
other letter in the alphabet,

00:09:17.190 --> 00:09:18.660
both uppercase and lowercase.

00:09:18.660 --> 00:09:20.940
But for reasons beyond
my comprehension,

00:09:20.940 --> 00:09:24.110
R just destroys you.

00:09:24.110 --> 00:09:24.705
Look at this.

00:09:30.910 --> 00:09:33.710
How does that happen?

00:09:33.710 --> 00:09:37.717
How do you mess
something up that badly?

00:09:37.717 --> 00:09:39.050
The first one is understandable.

00:09:39.050 --> 00:09:41.780
But what's going on
with that middle one?

00:09:41.780 --> 00:09:45.900
Have did that extra
protrusion get there?

00:09:45.900 --> 00:09:48.460
And look at the tiny
one on the right.

00:09:48.460 --> 00:09:49.870
That one has four protrusions.

00:09:53.356 --> 00:09:54.730
I'm not an expert
on protrusions,

00:09:54.730 --> 00:09:55.730
but that's way too many.

00:09:59.919 --> 00:10:01.960
I think if you took some
time to relax and really

00:10:01.960 --> 00:10:04.660
look at the letter R, you'd
see that it's not nearly as

00:10:04.660 --> 00:10:06.110
complicated as you're making it.

00:10:08.517 --> 00:10:09.350
Dear seven-year-old.

00:10:20.022 --> 00:10:21.605
Look at the other
children around you.

00:10:25.600 --> 00:10:28.665
Do you see how they're
wearing clothing?

00:10:28.665 --> 00:10:30.290
That's because they're
seven years old,

00:10:30.290 --> 00:10:31.706
and they've all
realized that it's

00:10:31.706 --> 00:10:34.780
no longer appropriate to take
their clothes off in public.

00:10:34.780 --> 00:10:37.446
But you haven't
realized that, have you?

00:10:37.446 --> 00:10:39.070
People have tried to
explain it to you.

00:10:39.070 --> 00:10:39.890
Your teachers have tried.

00:10:39.890 --> 00:10:41.000
Your parents have tried.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:43.041
Even the other students
have expressed discomfort

00:10:43.041 --> 00:10:46.240
with your persistent and
inexplicable nakedness.

00:10:46.240 --> 00:10:48.730
But you just don't stop.

00:10:48.730 --> 00:10:50.865
Why do you want to
be naked so badly?

00:10:50.865 --> 00:10:52.370
Do you even know why?

00:10:52.370 --> 00:10:54.460
Are you overtaken by
forces beyond your control

00:10:54.460 --> 00:10:55.490
that make you do this?

00:11:02.310 --> 00:11:04.140
Regardless, clothing
is a reality

00:11:04.140 --> 00:11:05.540
that you need to accept.

00:11:05.540 --> 00:11:07.034
There are no loopholes to this.

00:11:07.034 --> 00:11:08.700
You can't take your
clothes off and hide

00:11:08.700 --> 00:11:11.122
in the corner hoping
no one notices.

00:11:11.122 --> 00:11:12.830
You can't trick the
teachers into letting

00:11:12.830 --> 00:11:14.896
you be naked by burying
yourself in the sandbox.

00:11:17.845 --> 00:11:19.470
Your clothes are in
a pile next to you.

00:11:19.470 --> 00:11:19.990
They know.

00:11:25.482 --> 00:11:26.190
Dear 10-year-old.

00:11:31.550 --> 00:11:32.930
Wow, you really like dogs.

00:11:35.760 --> 00:11:37.840
In fact, you like dogs
so much, that I'm not

00:11:37.840 --> 00:11:40.240
even sure it's
emotionally healthy.

00:11:40.240 --> 00:11:42.740
It might be normal
to love dogs a lot,

00:11:42.740 --> 00:11:44.590
or to be really
interested in dogs.

00:11:44.590 --> 00:11:46.767
But you go way, way past that.

00:11:46.767 --> 00:11:48.600
Normal children don't
walk around pretending

00:11:48.600 --> 00:11:51.900
to be a dog nearly as much
as you do, for example.

00:11:51.900 --> 00:11:52.520
You're 10.

00:11:52.520 --> 00:11:54.880
It makes people wonder about
your developmental progress

00:11:54.880 --> 00:11:58.230
when you growl and bark at them.

00:11:58.230 --> 00:12:00.882
An even more concerning
issue is the obstacle course.

00:12:00.882 --> 00:12:03.340
Fine, you want to train your
dog to run through an obstacle

00:12:03.340 --> 00:12:04.100
course.

00:12:04.100 --> 00:12:05.130
That's pretty normal.

00:12:05.130 --> 00:12:07.440
What isn't normal is
making your mother time you

00:12:07.440 --> 00:12:11.820
as you crawl through
the course on all fours

00:12:11.820 --> 00:12:13.154
over and over again.

00:12:13.154 --> 00:12:15.070
You're making mom think
that she did something

00:12:15.070 --> 00:12:16.195
wrong to make you this way.

00:12:24.981 --> 00:12:26.730
Now that we've gotten
that out of the way,

00:12:26.730 --> 00:12:29.230
allow me answer your questions.

00:12:29.230 --> 00:12:30.850
Do you still like dogs?

00:12:30.850 --> 00:12:34.900
Yes, but not as much as you do.

00:12:34.900 --> 00:12:37.660
I've developed a healthy
relationship with dogs.

00:12:37.660 --> 00:12:39.600
What is your favorite dog?

00:12:39.600 --> 00:12:40.376
I don't know.

00:12:40.376 --> 00:12:41.750
This may cause a
surprise to you,

00:12:41.750 --> 00:12:44.160
but knowing exactly where
each dog breed ranks

00:12:44.160 --> 00:12:46.160
on my list of favorites
isn't the pressing issue

00:12:46.160 --> 00:12:47.935
that it used to be.

00:12:47.935 --> 00:12:50.180
Do you have a job training dogs?

00:12:50.180 --> 00:12:50.680
No.

00:12:50.680 --> 00:12:52.388
I can't even train my
own dogs, let alone

00:12:52.388 --> 00:12:54.960
the dogs of other people.

00:12:54.960 --> 00:12:56.960
Is Murphy still alive?

00:12:56.960 --> 00:12:57.760
Of course not.

00:13:02.105 --> 00:13:03.480
I don't know
whether you're being

00:13:03.480 --> 00:13:05.313
optimistic are you
actually don't understand

00:13:05.313 --> 00:13:07.044
that dogs won't live to be 25.

00:13:07.044 --> 00:13:09.460
But you really set yourself
up for a lot of disappointment

00:13:09.460 --> 00:13:11.420
there.

00:13:11.420 --> 00:13:12.840
What is your favorite food?

00:13:12.840 --> 00:13:13.590
Nachos.

00:13:13.590 --> 00:13:15.030
Which is fortunate,
because in the future,

00:13:15.030 --> 00:13:17.405
you're dysfunctional and you
don't take care of yourself.

00:13:17.405 --> 00:13:20.550
So you end up eating
a whole lot of nachos.

00:13:20.550 --> 00:13:22.400
Are mom and dad still alive?

00:13:22.400 --> 00:13:24.000
Actually, you turn
out to be Batman,

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.291
so we had to have them put
down for storyline purposes.

00:13:29.930 --> 00:13:32.750
Dear 13-year-old.

00:13:32.750 --> 00:13:35.200
I think everyone was relieved
when you started to grow out

00:13:35.200 --> 00:13:37.460
of your unhealthy
obsession with dogs.

00:13:37.460 --> 00:13:39.540
Unfortunately, now you
think you're a wizard.

00:13:45.870 --> 00:13:49.760
I know this because I found
your collection of spells.

00:13:49.760 --> 00:13:52.099
Tell me, how does mixing
dijon mustard with sand,

00:13:52.099 --> 00:13:53.890
and then eating it,
makes someone love you?

00:13:53.890 --> 00:13:59.629
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:59.629 --> 00:14:01.670
First of all, I thought
that your extensive early

00:14:01.670 --> 00:14:04.510
experiences with ingesting
nonfood substances

00:14:04.510 --> 00:14:07.240
would put you off of
attempting something like this.

00:14:07.240 --> 00:14:08.930
Secondly, no one is
going to love you

00:14:08.930 --> 00:14:11.471
until you stop doing things like
trying to make them love you

00:14:11.471 --> 00:14:12.520
by eating mustard sand.

00:14:15.370 --> 00:14:17.290
Dear other iterations
of my past self.

00:14:20.050 --> 00:14:24.979
Thank you for not
being so goddamn

00:14:24.979 --> 00:14:27.020
weird that I felt I had
to address you personally

00:14:27.020 --> 00:14:28.310
in a letter from the future.

00:14:28.310 --> 00:14:30.373
I commend you.

00:14:30.373 --> 00:14:31.846
The end.

00:14:31.846 --> 00:14:47.090
[APPLAUSE]

00:14:47.090 --> 00:14:48.620
So, questions I guess, now?

00:14:57.180 --> 00:14:57.721
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:14:57.721 --> 00:14:58.387
ALLIE BROSH: Hi.

00:14:58.387 --> 00:15:00.387
AUDIENCE: What's your
writing process like?

00:15:00.387 --> 00:15:01.220
ALLIE BROSH: Oh boy.

00:15:01.220 --> 00:15:02.190
OK.

00:15:02.190 --> 00:15:08.710
So I start out with a really
specific but vague sense

00:15:08.710 --> 00:15:10.360
of what I want the
post to feel like

00:15:10.360 --> 00:15:12.360
and what I want it to read like.

00:15:12.360 --> 00:15:13.855
The problem with
that is that it's

00:15:13.855 --> 00:15:15.230
sort of like
looking at something

00:15:15.230 --> 00:15:16.480
out of your peripheral vision.

00:15:16.480 --> 00:15:18.360
You can't really focus on it.

00:15:18.360 --> 00:15:20.400
And so you have to just
steer closer to it.

00:15:20.400 --> 00:15:21.900
And you know when
it's really wrong.

00:15:21.900 --> 00:15:23.790
You don't know when it's right.

00:15:23.790 --> 00:15:26.070
So most of the
writing a post process

00:15:26.070 --> 00:15:27.780
is just steering
it closer to what

00:15:27.780 --> 00:15:31.850
this arbitrary, weird mental
image I have in my head is.

00:15:31.850 --> 00:15:34.470
I also have a folder
system on my desktop.

00:15:34.470 --> 00:15:36.690
I have the idea farm.

00:15:36.690 --> 00:15:40.940
And that's where there's just
like one-word, random ideas.

00:15:40.940 --> 00:15:42.440
Sometimes I don't
even remember what

00:15:42.440 --> 00:15:44.400
I was thinking
when I wrote them.

00:15:44.400 --> 00:15:46.480
But I revisit that
folder periodically

00:15:46.480 --> 00:15:48.780
and try to see if there's
any new perspective that I

00:15:48.780 --> 00:15:51.320
have on one of those things.

00:15:51.320 --> 00:15:53.410
And if there is a
new perspective--

00:15:53.410 --> 00:15:55.560
like maybe a new angle,
something that can actually

00:15:55.560 --> 00:15:58.404
steer it toward being an
actual story with structure--

00:15:58.404 --> 00:15:59.820
I move it to another
folder, which

00:15:59.820 --> 00:16:02.370
is-- what's that one called.

00:16:02.370 --> 00:16:05.922
I think it's post-holding area.

00:16:05.922 --> 00:16:07.880
And that's where I start
actually working on it

00:16:07.880 --> 00:16:09.220
legitimately.

00:16:09.220 --> 00:16:10.850
And then once it
starts taking shape,

00:16:10.850 --> 00:16:12.010
to the point where I
feel like I can maybe

00:16:12.010 --> 00:16:14.140
start adding drawings,
I move it to the folder

00:16:14.140 --> 00:16:18.040
called "Look at
this, motherfucker."

00:16:18.040 --> 00:16:19.510
And that's to get
me to look at it.

00:16:22.597 --> 00:16:26.164
Because I won't otherwise.

00:16:26.164 --> 00:16:27.580
And then once it's
in that folder,

00:16:27.580 --> 00:16:30.121
I know that it's serious and I
need to take it very seriously

00:16:30.121 --> 00:16:31.779
and start drawing pictures.

00:16:31.779 --> 00:16:33.070
Does that answer your question?

00:16:35.690 --> 00:16:36.810
All right.

00:16:36.810 --> 00:16:37.860
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:16:37.860 --> 00:16:39.860
As someone who has
had dead fish before,

00:16:39.860 --> 00:16:41.660
I can say that I
really appreciated

00:16:41.660 --> 00:16:43.390
that particular comic.

00:16:43.390 --> 00:16:45.900
And I think it was
widely recognized

00:16:45.900 --> 00:16:49.740
as something that was very human
and an interesting, different

00:16:49.740 --> 00:16:52.640
perspective on
the subject than I

00:16:52.640 --> 00:16:54.530
think many other people
had ever seen before.

00:16:54.530 --> 00:16:56.972
And I think that was really
courageous and great.

00:16:56.972 --> 00:16:57.930
ALLIE BROSH: Thank you.

00:16:57.930 --> 00:16:59.300
AUDIENCE: Thank you
for writing that.

