00:17:28.950 --> 00:17:29.991
And now it's a shark fin.

00:17:33.720 --> 00:17:34.680
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:17:34.680 --> 00:17:36.370
I just wanted to
say, first of all,

00:17:36.370 --> 00:17:40.620
that I don't know if it's the
same post that guy was talking

00:17:40.620 --> 00:17:42.660
about, but I really,
really loved the post

00:17:42.660 --> 00:17:47.280
about Allie trying to kill the
fish, then she would spare it.

00:17:47.280 --> 00:17:48.466
Yeah, that was my favorite.

00:17:48.466 --> 00:17:49.590
I was cracking up for ages.

00:17:49.590 --> 00:17:52.140
But anyways, I wanted
to ask, you always

00:17:52.140 --> 00:17:54.760
seem to have this wealth of
ideas that you write about.

00:17:54.760 --> 00:17:56.920
And I was wondering how
you prevent yourself

00:17:56.920 --> 00:17:59.690
from hitting blogger's block?

00:17:59.690 --> 00:18:03.670
ALLIE BROSH: Well, I feel like I
thought that I was out of ideas

00:18:03.670 --> 00:18:08.100
pretty much like three weeks
after I started my blog.

00:18:08.100 --> 00:18:09.580
And I don't know.

00:18:09.580 --> 00:18:12.840
I just keep going back
to it and keep trying.

00:18:12.840 --> 00:18:15.280
Like I said, I write down
in may ideas farm thing,

00:18:15.280 --> 00:18:16.307
I just will write down.

00:18:16.307 --> 00:18:18.140
Even if I think something's
a horrible idea,

00:18:18.140 --> 00:18:19.515
I'll write it down
anyway if it's

00:18:19.515 --> 00:18:22.410
a word that maybe is intriguing.

00:18:22.410 --> 00:18:25.030
And I've had stuff where I come
back to it three years later.

00:18:25.030 --> 00:18:25.988
And it's like, finally.

00:18:25.988 --> 00:18:27.790
OK, now I can do
something with this.

00:18:27.790 --> 00:18:30.400
Whereas before, I maybe
hadn't had the experience yet

00:18:30.400 --> 00:18:33.840
that would allow me to turn
that actually into a story.

00:18:33.840 --> 00:18:36.560
There are some stories that
are you had to be there

00:18:36.560 --> 00:18:41.000
stories, until I figure out
what the little ironies are,

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:43.730
what the little inconsistencies
are in the story

00:18:43.730 --> 00:18:45.840
to draw out to make
it actually funny

00:18:45.840 --> 00:18:48.667
and read like there's
a structure to it.

00:18:48.667 --> 00:18:49.500
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:18:49.500 --> 00:18:50.666
ALLIE BROSH: You're welcome.

00:18:53.059 --> 00:18:54.053
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:18:54.053 --> 00:18:56.050
ALLIE BROSH: Oh, hi.

00:18:56.050 --> 00:18:58.185
I like your cone.

00:18:58.185 --> 00:18:59.610
That's good.

00:18:59.610 --> 00:19:03.890
[APPLAUSE]

00:19:03.890 --> 00:19:08.470
AUDIENCE: So your drawings have
this amazing like-- they're

00:19:08.470 --> 00:19:11.730
deformed in these weird
ways that are also,

00:19:11.730 --> 00:19:15.027
they seem to get across
the emotion more than

00:19:15.027 --> 00:19:16.860
if it was just like a
normal looking person.

00:19:16.860 --> 00:19:19.490
I'm wondering, do
you know beforehand

00:19:19.490 --> 00:19:22.200
how you're going to deform
a face that it looks

00:19:22.200 --> 00:19:25.634
so proud and so twisted, or do
you try like a million times?

00:19:25.634 --> 00:19:27.550
ALLIE BROSH: I do have
to try a million times.

00:19:27.550 --> 00:19:29.049
Like what I was
saying before, where

00:19:29.049 --> 00:19:31.700
I have this really vague
but very specific thing.

00:19:31.700 --> 00:19:34.480
If that makes sense.

00:19:34.480 --> 00:19:35.990
It's a specific sense.

00:19:35.990 --> 00:19:38.350
But the image in
my head is vague.

00:19:38.350 --> 00:19:42.270
And I have to do quite a
few drafts of my drawings

00:19:42.270 --> 00:19:46.340
to get it to look somewhat
close to what I'm imagining.

00:19:46.340 --> 00:19:48.130
And so sometimes,
it's actually good

00:19:48.130 --> 00:19:49.600
that I don't know what
I'm doing, because I'll

00:19:49.600 --> 00:19:50.860
draw something and
I'll be like, oh hey,

00:19:50.860 --> 00:19:52.276
I wouldn't have
thought of drawing

00:19:52.276 --> 00:19:55.590
that face if I didn't
just take a stab at it.

00:19:55.590 --> 00:19:58.270
But yeah, it definitely
takes a really long time

00:19:58.270 --> 00:20:00.070
to get the face just right.

00:20:00.070 --> 00:20:02.920
Sometimes the people,
the eye, if you

00:20:02.920 --> 00:20:04.890
move it even like
half a millimeter,

00:20:04.890 --> 00:20:07.279
it makes a huge difference
in the facial expression.

00:20:07.279 --> 00:20:08.820
And you wouldn't
think that something

00:20:08.820 --> 00:20:10.640
like that would make
such a big difference.

00:20:10.640 --> 00:20:13.087
But I guess maybe
just to me it does.

00:20:13.087 --> 00:20:14.420
AUDIENCE: Well, they're awesome.

00:20:14.420 --> 00:20:14.920
Thank you.

00:20:14.920 --> 00:20:17.650
ALLIE BROSH: You're welcome.

00:20:17.650 --> 00:20:20.230
AUDIENCE: Did you intentionally
hit on the artistic style

00:20:20.230 --> 00:20:22.280
and keep it consistent
intentionally,

00:20:22.280 --> 00:20:24.856
or is this just the
thing that came out?

00:20:24.856 --> 00:20:26.730
ALLIE BROSH: This is
the thing that came out.

00:20:26.730 --> 00:20:29.990
It's been an evolution.

00:20:29.990 --> 00:20:31.780
When I first started
drawing my character,

00:20:31.780 --> 00:20:36.510
it was just like a circle head
with a triangle body thing.

00:20:36.510 --> 00:20:40.330
And since then, there
are things like edits

00:20:40.330 --> 00:20:43.710
I've made to it that have slowly
made it what it is today, which

00:20:43.710 --> 00:20:47.500
is sort of like this
fish-tadpole-bird thing,

00:20:47.500 --> 00:20:49.760
I don't know what.

00:20:49.760 --> 00:20:52.758
All the shapes that I
find funny, I guess.

00:20:56.570 --> 00:20:59.310
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:20:59.310 --> 00:21:02.280
I think your work is really
relatable to a ton of people,

00:21:02.280 --> 00:21:04.880
because of how genuine it feels.

00:21:04.880 --> 00:21:07.540
You're part of a generation
of authors like Jenny Lawson

00:21:07.540 --> 00:21:11.250
and Matt [? Eiman ?] that
you just read their stuff

00:21:11.250 --> 00:21:13.899
and you feel so much
like this is something

00:21:13.899 --> 00:21:15.190
that could have happened to me.

00:21:15.190 --> 00:21:18.290
Or I remember something
that happened me now

00:21:18.290 --> 00:21:19.390
that exactly is like that.

00:21:19.390 --> 00:21:21.380
I wonder though,
since you're also

00:21:21.380 --> 00:21:23.930
a great comedian,
how much of what

00:21:23.930 --> 00:21:26.880
you write over the last
four or five years,

00:21:26.880 --> 00:21:28.160
do you feel detached from it?

00:21:28.160 --> 00:21:29.340
Or do you truly feel
like you're doing

00:21:29.340 --> 00:21:30.760
something autobiographical?

00:21:30.760 --> 00:21:32.440
Like, do look back
at things you wrote

00:21:32.440 --> 00:21:35.640
and you're like, no, that's
exactly how I feel now.

00:21:35.640 --> 00:21:39.190
Or do you feel like you
iterate over, again and again,

00:21:39.190 --> 00:21:41.830
to make it more of
a polished product?

00:21:41.830 --> 00:21:44.990
ALLIE BROSH: I definitely
spend a lot of time polishing.

00:21:44.990 --> 00:21:49.490
I think that my job as
a writer or a comedian

00:21:49.490 --> 00:21:51.630
is to take whatever
thing is in my head

00:21:51.630 --> 00:21:53.560
and figure out how
to translate it most

00:21:53.560 --> 00:21:55.610
faithfully into
other people's hands.

00:21:55.610 --> 00:21:59.310
And so, that involves a lot
of very specific word choices.

00:21:59.310 --> 00:22:02.970
So most of the editing process
is just getting the word

00:22:02.970 --> 00:22:06.380
choices down exactly
right to-- it

00:22:06.380 --> 00:22:10.420
can be the subtleties and shades
that I'm trying to get across.

00:22:10.420 --> 00:22:15.090
As far as how I feel
looking back on stories,

00:22:15.090 --> 00:22:17.460
I think I do put myself
in my head-- like,

00:22:17.460 --> 00:22:21.040
say when I'm a kid-- I write
from my perspective as a kid.

00:22:21.040 --> 00:22:23.685
So my mom is very much the
villain from my perspective.

00:22:26.645 --> 00:22:28.270
Clearly, from the
reader's perspective,

00:22:28.270 --> 00:22:30.810
she's just being a good mom
and doing what she needs to do.

00:22:30.810 --> 00:22:33.250
But yeah, so from my
perspective as a kid,

00:22:33.250 --> 00:22:36.637
she was being mean
and evil, and I

00:22:36.637 --> 00:22:37.970
think that answers the question.

00:22:37.970 --> 00:22:39.180
I feel like I'm rambling.

00:22:39.180 --> 00:22:40.305
AUDIENCE: No, that's great.

00:22:40.305 --> 00:22:42.590
Thanks

00:22:42.590 --> 00:22:43.750
ALLIE BROSH: Hi.

