00:24:46.090 --> 00:24:46.590
Yeah.

00:24:50.730 --> 00:24:53.260
AUDIENCE: So what made
you start drawing this?

00:24:53.260 --> 00:24:54.410
Did it start with the blog?

00:24:54.410 --> 00:24:56.430
Did you just draw
things like this

00:24:56.430 --> 00:24:58.310
and tell stories about
yourself in the past?

00:24:58.310 --> 00:24:59.060
ALLIE BROSH: Yeah.

00:24:59.060 --> 00:25:01.490
I mean, I've always
written stories just

00:25:01.490 --> 00:25:03.260
as a means to entertain myself.

00:25:03.260 --> 00:25:05.270
I used to try to write
books when I was a kid.

00:25:05.270 --> 00:25:08.340
They were mostly about guys
fighting things and just going

00:25:08.340 --> 00:25:11.840
on adventures where
they fight more things.

00:25:11.840 --> 00:25:14.900
So yeah, I guess I was
procrastinating when I actually

00:25:14.900 --> 00:25:16.950
started my blog.

00:25:16.950 --> 00:25:19.140
I was supposed to be
studying for a physics final

00:25:19.140 --> 00:25:20.600
for college.

00:25:20.600 --> 00:25:23.140
And I eventually
did study for it,

00:25:23.140 --> 00:25:25.960
but at this particular
point, I didn't want to.

00:25:25.960 --> 00:25:28.780
And I started to
write stuff online.

00:25:28.780 --> 00:25:31.159
And I think the
my style evolved--

00:25:31.159 --> 00:25:32.950
I've been thinking a
lot about this lately,

00:25:32.950 --> 00:25:39.331
actually-- it's probably
a result, sorry.

00:25:39.331 --> 00:25:41.080
I got like 45 minutes
of sleep last night,

00:25:41.080 --> 00:25:45.254
so I'm a little
scrambled in the brain.

00:25:45.254 --> 00:25:46.670
It's a result of
me subconsciously

00:25:46.670 --> 00:25:51.120
trying to reproduce the feel
of stand up comedy on the page.

00:25:51.120 --> 00:25:52.920
I watch a lot of
stand up comedy.

00:25:52.920 --> 00:25:55.307
And when I first
started just trying

00:25:55.307 --> 00:25:57.140
to write without the
pictures, I was sort of

00:25:57.140 --> 00:26:00.490
bothered by the fact that there
weren't facial expressions,

00:26:00.490 --> 00:26:03.550
or weren't any of
those non-verbal cues

00:26:03.550 --> 00:26:06.120
that you can get from
watching a stand up comedian.

00:26:06.120 --> 00:26:08.210
And so once I started
experimenting with pictures,

00:26:08.210 --> 00:26:10.497
it felt really natural
to have this thing

00:26:10.497 --> 00:26:12.080
that you can intersperse
with the text

00:26:12.080 --> 00:26:14.950
to give maybe like a
word list interaction.

00:26:14.950 --> 00:26:18.020
Or you could say
1,000 things at once,

00:26:18.020 --> 00:26:21.930
which is really helpful
for comedic timing.

00:26:21.930 --> 00:26:23.440
So that's how that happened.

00:26:29.738 --> 00:26:30.700
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:26:30.700 --> 00:26:33.420
How do you remember, or
make up, all the details

00:26:33.420 --> 00:26:35.542
about when you were a kid?

00:26:35.542 --> 00:26:40.290
[LAUGHTER]

00:26:40.290 --> 00:26:42.900
ALLIE BROSH: My memory
starts pretty young.

00:26:42.900 --> 00:26:46.540
I have all right memories
of most of the early stuff.

00:26:46.540 --> 00:26:49.760
So if I write stories of
when I'm like four and five,

00:26:49.760 --> 00:26:51.250
the memories are
a little spotty.

00:26:51.250 --> 00:26:52.800
I have to talk to
my mom about some

00:26:52.800 --> 00:26:57.190
of the more storyline
relevant details, about like,

00:26:57.190 --> 00:26:59.020
for example, in the
post about the cake,

00:26:59.020 --> 00:27:01.390
meeting the entire cake.

00:27:01.390 --> 00:27:03.100
I remember everything
about that,

00:27:03.100 --> 00:27:05.433
except for I don't actually
know how I got into the room

00:27:05.433 --> 00:27:06.355
with the cake.

00:27:06.355 --> 00:27:07.230
I remember eating it.

00:27:07.230 --> 00:27:09.104
I remember throwing it
up all over the place.

00:27:09.104 --> 00:27:11.080
But I don't remember
how I got in there.

00:27:11.080 --> 00:27:13.890
So with stuff like that, where
I really don't remember--

00:27:13.890 --> 00:27:15.975
and it's not a major
like, it's something

00:27:15.975 --> 00:27:17.600
like I got into the
room with the cake.

00:27:17.600 --> 00:27:20.370
So I just need to find a
way to get to that point.

00:27:20.370 --> 00:27:22.590
And I figured the most
logical explanation, knowing

00:27:22.590 --> 00:27:25.240
my grandparents'
house, was the window.

00:27:25.240 --> 00:27:26.920
So there's a little bit of that.

00:27:26.920 --> 00:27:30.620
And sometimes I'll trim stuff
down for like streamlining it

00:27:30.620 --> 00:27:32.800
for storyline purposes,
so it's not confusing.

00:27:32.800 --> 00:27:34.672
Or, say like, oh,
well I was here

00:27:34.672 --> 00:27:36.630
with this person, this
person, and this person.

00:27:36.630 --> 00:27:40.070
I'll just like, I was here.

00:27:40.070 --> 00:27:45.500
But yeah, they're-- you were
asking about my memories.

00:27:45.500 --> 00:27:48.150
I'm really sorry, you guys.

00:27:48.150 --> 00:27:51.120
I knew I was going to
crash at some point today.

00:27:51.120 --> 00:27:53.360
I woke up and I was so
surprised like, oh man, I

00:27:53.360 --> 00:27:57.014
don't feel like as bad as
I thought I would feel.

00:27:57.014 --> 00:27:58.930
And now, it's all starting
to come back to me.

00:27:58.930 --> 00:28:00.809
It's catching up.

00:28:00.809 --> 00:28:02.100
So yeah, hang in there with me.

00:28:02.100 --> 00:28:04.488
I'm sorry.

00:28:04.488 --> 00:28:06.120
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:28:06.120 --> 00:28:07.650
What would you say
distinguishes you

00:28:07.650 --> 00:28:12.217
from your character
named Allie, if anything?

00:28:12.217 --> 00:28:14.300
ALLIE BROSH: I think that
my character is actually

00:28:14.300 --> 00:28:16.730
a more accurate
representation of me,

00:28:16.730 --> 00:28:19.530
like how I really, really am.

00:28:19.530 --> 00:28:21.300
It's like inside.

00:28:21.300 --> 00:28:22.550
Inside that, that's what I am.

00:28:22.550 --> 00:28:24.330
I'm this weird, absurd thing.

00:28:26.840 --> 00:28:28.810
And yeah, like when
I talk to myself,

00:28:28.810 --> 00:28:32.620
the voice inside my head
is very much this thing.

00:28:32.620 --> 00:28:34.810
Me, I'm just yeah.

00:28:34.810 --> 00:28:37.796
I relate more to the character.

00:28:37.796 --> 00:28:39.277
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:39.277 --> 00:28:39.985
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:28:42.660 --> 00:28:44.280
ALLIE BROSH: I
love your costume.

00:28:44.280 --> 00:28:45.439
AUDIENCE: What costume?

00:28:45.439 --> 00:28:46.377
ALLIE BROSH: Oh.

00:28:46.377 --> 00:28:50.130
[LAUGHTER AND APPLAUSE]

00:28:50.130 --> 00:28:51.930
AUDIENCE: Thank you for coming.

00:28:51.930 --> 00:28:54.730
I was hoping you could
talk a little bit about how

00:28:54.730 --> 00:28:58.260
early you get feedback on posts,
how polished you like things

00:28:58.260 --> 00:29:01.600
to be before you get
it, who you go to.

00:29:01.600 --> 00:29:04.100
ALLIE BROSH: I pretty much just
talk to my husband about it.

00:29:04.100 --> 00:29:08.180
He's the only one in like
the inner, inner post circle.

00:29:08.180 --> 00:29:10.425
Because I start to
doubt myself when

00:29:10.425 --> 00:29:13.050
I'm hammering through
stuff that never

00:29:13.050 --> 00:29:14.780
sounds funny in
the very beginning.

00:29:14.780 --> 00:29:16.690
Because I'm stumbling over
it, and I'm like oh, well,

00:29:16.690 --> 00:29:17.200
there's this part.

00:29:17.200 --> 00:29:18.640
And it'll be really
funny, you'll see.

00:29:18.640 --> 00:29:20.320
Like, once I draw the
picture, once I draw the eyes,

00:29:20.320 --> 00:29:21.260
you'll see it'll
be really funny.

00:29:21.260 --> 00:29:22.320
But just imagine this.

00:29:22.320 --> 00:29:24.930
And you don't get
the whole picture.

00:29:24.930 --> 00:29:29.250
So I do just read it to Duncan.

00:29:29.250 --> 00:29:32.340
I guess I share with my editor
and my agent sometimes too.

00:29:32.340 --> 00:29:34.270
But most of it just
goes on in my own head.

00:29:34.270 --> 00:29:38.290
I leave it for a few days if
I'm really stuck, and come back

00:29:38.290 --> 00:29:39.792
and read it and think like, hey.

00:29:39.792 --> 00:29:41.500
Is this any better
than I thought it was?

00:29:41.500 --> 00:29:43.360
Or maybe I missed something?

00:29:43.360 --> 00:29:45.420
Maybe I think it's horrible now?

00:29:45.420 --> 00:29:47.640
AUDIENCE: Do you ever
talk to your husband

00:29:47.640 --> 00:29:49.440
to get ideas to get you unstuck?

00:29:49.440 --> 00:29:50.440
ALLIE BROSH: Yeah, yeah.

00:29:50.440 --> 00:29:52.606
We'll go on walks, these
like long, nighttime walks,

00:29:52.606 --> 00:29:54.270
and just like hammer
out post ideas.

00:29:54.270 --> 00:29:59.130
And we'll pick a topic, like
identity, and say like, well.

00:29:59.130 --> 00:30:02.940
What's important
for your identity?

00:30:02.940 --> 00:30:05.460
And he'll say to me what's
important for his identity,

00:30:05.460 --> 00:30:06.876
and then we'll
just talk about it.

00:30:06.876 --> 00:30:08.474
And it's good,
because we just have

00:30:08.474 --> 00:30:10.390
an interesting conversation,
and maybe an idea

00:30:10.390 --> 00:30:11.550
will spring from that.

00:30:11.550 --> 00:30:12.800
AUDIENCE: Thank you very much.

00:30:12.800 --> 00:30:13.966
ALLIE BROSH: You're welcome.

00:30:16.450 --> 00:30:18.590
AUDIENCE: We also have
30% of our offices

00:30:18.590 --> 00:30:20.057
on a Hangout view this.

00:30:20.057 --> 00:30:22.390
And so if anyone on the Hangout
wants to ask a question,

00:30:22.390 --> 00:30:25.460
just unmute in between
questions, and ask away.

00:30:25.460 --> 00:30:29.070
And I think we have time
for five more minutes.

00:30:29.070 --> 00:30:30.510
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:30:30.510 --> 00:30:32.400
I'd like to ask a question.

00:30:32.400 --> 00:30:35.470
ALLIE BROSH: Where is it?

00:30:35.470 --> 00:30:37.367
AUDIENCE: I'm the
disembodied voice.

00:30:37.367 --> 00:30:38.450
ALLIE BROSH: I can see me.

00:30:38.450 --> 00:30:41.210
I can't see anybody--

00:30:41.210 --> 00:30:45.350
AUDIENCE: I, really, really,
really love your blog.

00:30:45.350 --> 00:30:50.260
And thank God you're
writing it to me.

00:30:50.260 --> 00:30:51.960
I used to have to pet rats.

00:30:51.960 --> 00:30:54.020
And I adored them.

00:30:54.020 --> 00:30:55.640
And I want to have
them again soon.

00:30:55.640 --> 00:30:58.810
But I'd like to know a bit
more about your pet rats.

00:30:58.810 --> 00:31:00.830
ALLIE BROSH: They're wonderful.

00:31:00.830 --> 00:31:03.030
I rescue them, actually.

00:31:03.030 --> 00:31:06.570
We adopt them
from-- so, you guys

00:31:06.570 --> 00:31:11.640
have maybe seen the "Hoarders"
episode with the rats.

00:31:11.640 --> 00:31:13.314
We adopted some
from that situation.

00:31:13.314 --> 00:31:14.980
They took them out
of the house and were

00:31:14.980 --> 00:31:16.700
trying to get them homes.

00:31:16.700 --> 00:31:20.240
So we have, I think, seven now.

00:31:20.240 --> 00:31:24.480
And our oldest two rats are
just the sweetest two rats

00:31:24.480 --> 00:31:25.250
in the world.

00:31:25.250 --> 00:31:27.442
There's Pizzo, who
is my favorite thing

00:31:27.442 --> 00:31:28.400
in the entire universe.

00:31:28.400 --> 00:31:34.000
She's roughly potato-shaped
and very soft.

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:36.590
And she's very affectionate.

00:31:36.590 --> 00:31:42.480
And then there's Charlie,
who-- Charlie's very special.

00:31:42.480 --> 00:31:44.850
She never really settled down.

00:31:44.850 --> 00:31:47.280
She's sort of twitchy and
weird about everything.

00:31:47.280 --> 00:31:50.290
But I love her to death.

00:31:50.290 --> 00:31:52.630
And I could go
through all of them,

00:31:52.630 --> 00:31:55.840
but I think that wouldn't
leave very much time

00:31:55.840 --> 00:31:57.294
for other questions.

00:31:57.294 --> 00:31:59.460
AUDIENCE: But how do they
get along with helper dog?

00:32:02.095 --> 00:32:03.720
ALLIE BROSH: The dogs
leave them alone.

00:32:03.720 --> 00:32:07.440
They know that the
rat cage is special,

00:32:07.440 --> 00:32:10.907
and they shouldn't go
over there and bug them.

00:32:10.907 --> 00:32:11.740
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:32:11.740 --> 00:32:13.040
ALLIE BROSH: You're welcome.

00:32:13.040 --> 00:32:15.040
AUDIENCE: I was going to
ask if you've ever done

00:32:15.040 --> 00:32:17.250
or wanted to do any
spoken forms of comedy,

00:32:17.250 --> 00:32:19.267
like improv, stand
up, et cetera?

00:32:19.267 --> 00:32:21.350
ALLIE BROSH: I actually
would love to do stand up.

00:32:21.350 --> 00:32:23.450
I don't know if I have
the stage presence for it.

00:32:23.450 --> 00:32:25.280
It terrifies me.

00:32:25.280 --> 00:32:27.570
But I love stand up comedy.

00:32:27.570 --> 00:32:29.755
And maybe one of these days
I'll take a crack at it.

00:32:29.755 --> 00:32:30.630
AUDIENCE: You should.

00:32:30.630 --> 00:32:33.550
All kinds of people with
terrible stage presence do it.

00:32:33.550 --> 00:32:54.476
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:54.476 --> 00:32:56.100
AUDIENCE: So when
did you first realize

00:32:56.100 --> 00:32:58.210
that some of your characters
and their expressions

00:32:58.210 --> 00:32:59.880
left your blog and
were used for memes

00:32:59.880 --> 00:33:02.170
and other forms of
entertainment on the internet?

00:33:02.170 --> 00:33:04.610
And did that change
your writing at all?

00:33:04.610 --> 00:33:07.070
ALLIE BROSH: It didn't
change my writing.

00:33:07.070 --> 00:33:09.120
I noticed it when people
like my Facebook friends

00:33:09.120 --> 00:33:12.350
would post it on my wall, and
be like, did you see this?

00:33:12.350 --> 00:33:13.130
No, I did not.

00:33:16.482 --> 00:33:17.940
I think one of the
first ones I saw

00:33:17.940 --> 00:33:20.225
was somebody using it
on a coffee shop sign,

00:33:20.225 --> 00:33:22.190
with the chalk drawings.

00:33:22.190 --> 00:33:24.370
And that was pretty cool.

00:33:24.370 --> 00:33:26.430
And I see people
will make their own,

00:33:26.430 --> 00:33:30.336
and post Alot memes to my wall.

00:33:30.336 --> 00:33:31.460
Hey, I see it all the time.

00:33:31.460 --> 00:33:32.820
I'm always getting emails
from people being like,

00:33:32.820 --> 00:33:34.300
did you see this
one and this one?

00:33:36.577 --> 00:33:37.410
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:33:42.800 --> 00:33:45.010
AUDIENCE: As an artist
and a copyright holder,

00:33:45.010 --> 00:33:46.774
how do you feel about that?

00:33:46.774 --> 00:33:50.560
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:50.560 --> 00:33:53.060
ALLIE BROSH: I like that the
internet is having fun with it.

00:33:53.060 --> 00:33:56.610
It's fine when people are
just using it as a meme.

00:33:56.610 --> 00:33:59.800
Having fun with it, trying to
be funny, that's totally fine.

00:33:59.800 --> 00:34:02.350
It's less fine when they are
using it to sell something

00:34:02.350 --> 00:34:06.730
or to like support a really
shitty point of view.

00:34:06.730 --> 00:34:08.909
I don't know.

00:34:08.909 --> 00:34:10.973
So those times really bother me.

00:34:10.973 --> 00:34:12.889
But the other times, I'm
totally fine with it,

00:34:12.889 --> 00:34:15.180
when people are just having
fun and trying to be funny.

00:34:21.602 --> 00:34:23.560
PRESENTER: I think that's
all we have time for.

00:34:23.560 --> 00:34:24.522
Thank you so much.

00:34:24.522 --> 00:34:26.480
Allie is going to be
signing books at the back.

00:34:26.480 --> 00:34:28.982
So if you want your book signed,
please make an orderly line

00:34:28.982 --> 00:34:30.190
towards the back of the room.

00:34:30.190 --> 00:34:31.539
Thank you so much for coming.

00:34:31.539 --> 00:34:40.321
[APPLAUSE]

